Latin America in the Fight Against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented magnitude and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not confront the crisis resolutely, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political responses in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, unfortunately, downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose, in the midst of the tragedy, a populist and divisive policy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
In addition, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other important resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump, whose reckless decision to freeze approximately 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has domestic production in Latin America been disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the lack of tourism and fewer foreign remittances, as well as significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring payments to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for businesses are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and wage-related costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at that point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – would be at risk.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon turn into a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment postponements, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Well-capitalized and managed state banks can also play a leading role in this.
Generally speaking, measures will vary from country to country, but overall, extraordinary fiscal resources will likely be required everywhere to accelerate recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening health risks.
The problem is that fiscal space in Latin America is today even narrower than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, fiscal burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
However, there is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can be reduced by the governments' commitment to correct the higher fiscal deficits within a reasonable period of time.
However, external support for households and balance sheets is urgently needed, particularly for the small and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and states incur higher deficits, the countries' current accounts are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the modern history of financial markets – exacerbate the problem even further.
The resulting currency depreciations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role here.
It must address the short-term currency and budgetary needs of countries and continue to support economies in this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
For this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a revival of the IMF's global reserve currency – special drawing rights (SDRs) – which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries based on their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the supervision of the Fund.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity by immediately doubling the volume of New Credit Arrangements to meet the upcoming strong credit demand.
Finally, since traditional IMF credit programs cannot be approved in a timely manner, the Fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with rapid disbursement - such as its Rapid Financing Instrument - or launch new credit facilities for the pandemic.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps - either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all available instruments and create new ones if necessary to supply financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
Finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide further fiscal support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit could be supplemented by debt relief.
The MEB should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role here.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and to show what it can offer citizens.
